WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
Please welcome Gordon Woodhull.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Thank you.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:09.000
I'd like to start out with a quick survey.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Could I get a show of hands for who prefers Dark Mode on their desktop or laptop computer?

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:23.000
And could I get a show of hands for who prefers Light Mode on their desktop or laptop computer?

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And who switches between the two or doesn't care?

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Yeah.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
So there's really a wide range of opinions on this.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
And the thing to remember is, you know, whichever one you prefer, there's a lot of people who like it the other way.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
So we really should be designing for both Light and Dark Mode.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
So we're going to see how Quarto makes that easier.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
But first, let's take a look at brand-yml.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Brand-yml is a simple and easy configuration language for doing the basics of brand.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Just the most important parts of it, which are the color, typography, and logo.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:13.000
No matter what kind of organization you work for, brand-yml provides a way for you to easily share

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:20.000
and get everybody having the same look between their different work.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:30.000
And also, brand-yml is compatible with both Shiny and most of Quarto's HTML, all the HTML formats and the types format.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
So how do we do Dark Mode in brand-yml?

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Well, we could simply just plug in a bunch of dark colors and a dark logo, and this totally works.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:48.000
But as we were saying, you really want to design for both Light and Dark Mode.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:55.000
So in Quarto 1.8, we support both having light and dark colors and light and dark logo.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And when you enable that, this gets you the toggle, but nobody wants to use that, right?

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Everybody just wants to see it the way they want to see it.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
So in Quarto 1.7, we introduced respect user color scheme.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:14.000
This just follows the system scheme, and it's dynamic for people who change between the two.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:20.000
If you've been watching closely, you notice that this plot, which is a map plot lib of a spiral,

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:26.000
has been faithfully following the background and foreground colors, even when we switch between Light and Dark Mode.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
So let's look at how that works.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
We're not going to get too much in the code, don't worry.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So we have first renderings, light, dark.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:39.000
It's a cell option that just says we're going to render first in Light Mode and second in Dark Mode.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:45.000
And you can see there's this light style and dark style, which enables Light Mode and then Dark Mode.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
Map plot lib is very imperative style, so you really just have to do it all again.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Other plotting libraries and table libraries that are more declarative, you can share more of the code.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And here you just define the plot once and then output it once in Light Mode and once in Dark Mode.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Similar for plot 9, for Altair, Plotly.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And I'm not showing just a little bit of the glue code that makes this all happen,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.000
but there's glue code in the Cordo-R and Cordo-Python packages

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
and the BrandyML package that makes this all possible.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
There's just a little bit of syntax that we haven't quite finalized yet,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
so watch out for that in the next couple of weeks.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
And there's a whole bunch of links here with all kinds of documentation and examples.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Please check it out. Thank you.

